# {{ name }} fragment skeleton

Generated by `forge --plugins scaffold-fragment --name {{ name }}`.

## What's here

```
{{ name }}/
├── fragments.py           # registers the Fragment via ForgeAPI.add_fragment
├── README.md              # this file
{%- for backend in backends %}
├── {{ backend }}/
│   ├── inject.yaml        # injection points (target / marker / snippet)
│   └── files/             # files copied verbatim into the generated backend
{%- endfor %}
```

## Next steps

1. **Register an `Option` that enables this fragment.** Fragments are
   implementation detail; users select Options. Add an `Option` in your
   plugin's `register(api)` whose `enables=` map points at
   `"{{ name }}"`. See `examples/forge-plugin-example/` for a worked
   example.
2. **Fill in `fragments.py`** — the file ships with TODO stubs for
   the `FragmentImplSpec` per backend. Add `dependencies=`, `env_vars=`,
   `reads_options=` as the fragment needs.
3. **Author per-backend `inject.yaml` entries.** Each entry needs a
   `target` (path inside the backend tree), a `marker` (an existing
   `FORGE:<NAME>` anchor in the base template), `position`
   (`before` / `after`), and a `snippet`. Run
   `forge --plan --dry-run` to verify the plan validator accepts it
   before generating a full project.
4. **Drop verbatim files into `<backend>/files/`** mirroring the
   backend tree root (e.g. `python/files/src/app/foo.py` lands at
   `<backend>/src/app/foo.py` and is importable as `app.foo`).
5. **Delete the placeholder root `inject.yaml`** — the real injection
   manifests live per-backend.

See `docs/plugin-development.md` for the full plugin authoring guide.
